Key Requirements for Better Broadcast Quality
1. Ultra-Low Latency Streaming
Esports viewers expect near real-time streaming.
High latency causes:
Delayed reactions
Spoilers from social media/chat
Poor viewer experience
Typical targets:
| Platform Type                     | Latency   |
| --------------------------------- | --------- |
| Traditional OTT                   | 20–40 sec |
| Standard Live Streaming           | 5–15 sec  |
| Esports Streaming                 | 1–5 sec   |
| Competitive Interactive Streaming | <1 sec    |

Technologies used:
WebRTC
Low-Latency HLS (LL-HLS)
Low-Latency DASH
SRT protocol
2. Adaptive Bitrate Streaming (ABR)
Network conditions continuously change.
ABR dynamically switches video quality:
240p
480p
720p
1080p
4K
without interrupting playback.
Benefits:
Reduces freezing
Prevents buffering
Maintains smooth playback
Common protocols:
HLS
MPEG-DASH

3. Efficient Video Compression
Esports contains:
Fast motion
Rapid scene changes
Detailed textures
HUD/UI overlays
Efficient codecs are essential.

Common codecs:
x264
x265
AOMedia Video 1

AV1 is increasingly preferred because it:
Improves quality at lower bitrate
Reduces CDN cost
Preserves gaming details

4. Real-Time Encoding
The platform must encode live gameplay instantly.

Important encoder features:
Fast motion estimation
Low-delay GOP structure
Real-time rate control
GPU acceleration

Hardware acceleration commonly uses:
NVIDIA NVENC
AMD AMF
Intel Quick Sync

5. Content Delivery Network (CDN)
Millions of viewers cannot be served from one server.
CDNs distribute video globally.
Functions:
Edge caching
Load balancing
Traffic optimization

Major CDN providers:
Cloudflare
Akamai Technologies
Amazon Web Services
Fastly

6. Anti-Freezing / Anti-Buffering Mechanisms
To avoid interruptions:
Intelligent buffering
Packet loss recovery
Forward error correction
Congestion control

Protocols used:
QUIC
SRT
RTP/RTCP

7. Scalability
Major esports events may attract:
Millions of concurrent users
The platform must support:
Dynamic scaling
Multi-region deployment
Cloud elasticity

Example events:
League of Legends World Championship
The International

8. High Frame Rate Streaming
Esports requires:
60 fps minimum
120 fps increasingly desirable

Higher frame rate improves:
Motion smoothness
Competitive visibility

Especially important for:
FPS games
Racing games
Battle royale games

9. AI-Based Streaming Optimization
Modern platforms use AI for:
Bandwidth prediction
Dynamic bitrate optimization
QoE monitoring
Scene-aware encoding

AI can allocate more bitrate to:
Fast action scenes
Explosions
Character motion

and less to static scenes.
This directly relates to deep-learning video compression research.

10. Quality of Experience (QoE)
QoE metrics include:
Startup delay
Rebuffering frequency
Visual quality
Latency stability

Platforms optimize:
Viewer satisfaction
Watch time
Retention

